@NODE "Mail_496" "Re: That HEX thing again"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 25 Aug 1999 05:06:48 -0500
Subject: Re: That HEX thing again
X-UIDL: d95ae89d1ffbd073be0f223d3219cf8c

--BOUNDARY.1748492728.1

Hi Gaz-JD/FX-s^D

>> 2} The variables stored in the file are probably all unsigned.  But Blitz
>> assumes that all variables are signed.  So, to get the correct value from
>> an unsigned byte:
> 
> signed/unsigned? WTF does that mean?

Signed means a number that can be positive or negative.

For example, -100 is a signed number.

But for your saved game file, there would be no point in storing negative
values.
Kills, for example, could be 0, or 150, but never -20...

An unsigned byte can store values from 0 to 255
A  signed  byte  can store values from -127 to +128

To read a byte as unsigned, you simply do "AND $FF" with it's value.

If you are reading an Unsigned Word, you use "AND $FFFF"

I've attached a small example which might help to explain it.

Later...
-- 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748492728.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="unsigned.asc"

;signed - and unsigned values
;or, how to fix Blitz's insistance on reading everything as signed  :)

;you must have OVERFLOW ERRORS turned off in the compiler options

byte1.b=50
byte2.b=163

NPrint "byte1 is set to 50"
NPrint "byte2 is set to 163"
NPrint " "
NPrint "Now, let's read their values in the usual way:"
NPrint "byte1 = ",byte1
NPrint "byte2 = ",byte2
NPrint " "
NPrint "See how Blitz gets the 163 wrong by treating it as signed..."
NPrint " "
NPrint "Now, let's read them as unsigned, by using AND $FF"
NPrint "byte1 = ",byte1 AND $FF
NPrint "byte2 = ",byte2 AND $FF


MouseWait
End




--BOUNDARY.1748492728.1

